      <text>
        Three weeks since the battle.

        The facility is almost unrecognizable — not because it's wrecked, though it was thoroughly — but because it's being rebuilt by committee. Weird, creative, enthusiastic committee of plants who apparently decided "just following the old plans" was boring.

        I'm standing in what used to be the common area, watching Runner emerge from underground with yet another adjustment to their network design.

        Runner asks, vines gesturing toward a bowl-shaped depression in the floor.
        "Kira, can you test the resonance chamber?"

        "The what now?"

        Runner gestures again. "Stand in the center and say something — I'm trying to create acoustically interesting spaces."

        I step into the depression. "Testing, testing."

        My voice echoes weirdly — not quite echo, more like harmony — like the space itself is singing along.

        ¶

        "That's incredible," I say, and the space turns it into something almost musical.

        Runner's vines ripple with satisfaction. "The underground network isn't just for transportation and communication anymore — I realized it could be…beautiful. Functional and aesthetic. Individual spaces with individual characteristics."

        "You're creating art."

        "I'm creating connection. But yes, also art."

        This is new. The old Runner would have followed underground construction protocols exactly — current Runner is designing underground chambers that sing.

        Velvet's growth is everywhere — but not the standard structural reinforcement I'm used to. They've created alcoves and spaces with specific purposes: sleeping areas with soft moss, meeting spots with pleasant proportions, even something that might be a garden — though calling it a garden feels inadequate when the gardener is itself a plant.

        Velvet calls from across the space. "Kira! Does this seating arrangement feel comfortable from human perspective?"

        I go over to examine their latest creation — growth shaped into seating with back support, appropriate height, even cushioning texture.

        "This is actually really comfortable," I say, sitting. "How did you know?"

        Velvet replies, "I asked you last week about human ergonomics — you said you'd show me your crash pod seat design. I extrapolated from there and tested prototypes."

        They created furniture for me — based on a conversation we had.

        "This is amazing, Velvet."

        "It's practical. But also..." Velvet's growth rustles. "I enjoy creating spaces that serve specific needs rather than just growing generically — everyone's voice about what they need helps me design better."

        Scout bounces over, happy and proud, having been helping everyone — bouncing between projects and providing what I've come to recognize as emotional support through presence.

        "Scout, what have you been working on?"

        Scout leads me to a section of wall where Velvet's growth has created small alcoves at Scout-height — personal storage and collection spaces.

        "Are these yours?"
      </text>
