        Affirmative bounce—each alcove contains something: interesting rocks, pretty leaves, items Scout has collected, arranged deliberately—curated.

        I say, "You made a gallery."

        Pleased bounce—Scout has been collecting beauty and wants to share it.

        I say, "I love it."

        Scout bounces, pure joy.

        Remedy is in their work area—it's been transformed too. Instead of only survival compounds, they're producing enhancements: colors, scents, things that make daily life better rather than merely possible.

        I say, "Remedy, what's that smell?"

        Remedy says, "Experimental aromatic compound—does it please your human olfactory system?"

        I breathe in. It's subtle, pleasant—reminds me of something I can't quite name. I say, "It's nice. Calming."

        Remedy says, "Good—I'm developing environmental enhancements. The facility should be comfortable, not just functional— I used to only think about survival chemistry—Velvet asked what I could do to make their growth smell better—Florence asked about tactical applications of scent for communication—Kira asked about human-safe fragrances—I've realized chemistry can serve joy, not just necessity."

        I say, "You're making perfume."

        Remedy replies, "I'm making life better."

        It's the same sentiment everyone's expressing: contribution beyond protocol—individual voices creating collective improvement.

        Holloway is coordinating all of this, but not controlling. They move between projects, offering suggestions, asking questions, helping people connect their individual efforts.

        Holloway asks Velvet, "How's the eastern section coming?"

        Velvet replies, "Structural integrity complete—now adding aesthetic elements based on Kira's feedback about human need for varied visual stimulation."

        Holloway asks Runner, "And Runner, can your acoustic network integrate with Velvet's aesthetic planning?"

        Runner replies, "Already designing connection points—the resonance chambers will flow naturally through Velvet's spaces."

        Holloway says, "Excellent. Florence, do the defensive considerations work with these layouts?"

        Florence wheels over—she's been consulting on facility design as one voice among many.

        Florence says, "The layout maintains defensive visibility while creating comfortable spaces—better than the old design, actually. The alcoves provide protection points without feeling like bunkers."

        Velvet adds, "Because Kira mentioned humans don't like feeling trapped."

        Runner notes, "And my acoustic chambers can serve as early warning systems."

        Remedy contributes, "And my scent markers can indicate safe zones."

        Everyone is building on each other's ideas—individual voices creating harmony.

        I'm watching this and feeling… something. Something I didn't expect.

        ¶

        Holloway asks me, "Kira, can you check the sight lines from human eye-level?"
      </text>
