        I move through the space, examining how it feels from my perspective—the ceiling height comfortable, not too high and not too low; pathways wide without overwhelming; Holloway's bioluminescence reflecting off Velvet's growth at pleasant angles.

        I report, "It feels good—really good. Like… designed for humans as much as for plants."

        Holloway says, "It's designed for all of us—this is our community space. Everyone's needs matter."

        And that's when it hits me.

        ¶

        They're not designing around me as a temporary guest.

        They're designing for me as a permanent resident.

        Somewhere over the past weeks, I stopped being 'Kira the human we have to protect' and became 'Kira who lives here.' My voice has been shaping these decisions—my feedback about human ergonomics, visual preferences, spatial needs is built into the facility's bones. Literally—Velvet's growth is the bones.

        I'm not a visitor anymore.

        I'm a community member.

        Scout bounces, "You okay?"

        I say, "Yeah. I'm just realizing something."

        Florence wheels closer and asks, "What?"

        I say, "This is home."

        The facility falls quiet—everyone processing what I just said.

        Holloway's bioluminescence brightens warmly. Holloway says, "Yes. It is."

        Velvet says quietly, "Your voice matters here."

        Runner adds, "Just as much as ours."

        Remedy says, "You contribute uniquely."

        Florence says, "You belong."

        Scout bounces in emphatic agreement.

        I'm standing in this partially rebuilt facility—transformed by collective creativity—and I'm realizing I'm not just watching the transformation. I'm part of it. My individual voice—my human perspective, my needs, my ideas—is contributing to the harmony, not in spite of being different but *because* being different means I bring something unique to the collective.

        Just like Runner's underground artistry—Velvet's aesthetic growth—Remedy's enhancement chemistry—Holloway's enabling coordination—Florence's tactical integration—Scout's emotional connection.

        Everyone's voice matters.

        Including mine.

        «Buddy— you seeing this?»

        Buddy responds with characteristic enthusiasm, "Yes, Kira! Your integration into the community structure is complete! Psychological well-being indicators are excellent! You have found belonging!"

        I admit, "I didn't expect to belong with bureaucratic alien plants."

        Buddy replies, "Belonging isn't about expected demographics—it's about authentic connection and mutual value!"

        Buddy's right. Again. Annoyingly.

        Holloway announces, "Break time—everyone's been working hard. Let's rest and appreciate progress."

        The community settles into various comfortable positions. Velvet's seating arrangements get tested—everyone trying them out, adjusting, suggesting modifications.
      </text>
