      <text>
        Runner demonstrates the acoustic chambers—different spaces creating different harmonics. It's weird and wonderful to hear plant voices resonate through intentionally designed architecture.

        Remedy shares experimental scents—some pleasant, some strange, and one that makes everyone immediately request they never produce it again. Absurdist comedy in plant perfume testing.

        Scout bounces between everyone, spreading social glue and making sure nobody's isolated.

        Florence participates equally—offering suggestions, accepting feedback, contributing without dominating. Her redemption arc is complete; she's not just valued despite past mistakes—she's integral to community function.

        And I'm here too, contributing, belonging.

        The facility is taking shape as something new—not restoration of old protocols but creation of new harmony. Individual voices working together.

        And somewhere in the past weeks, without quite noticing when, I found my voice in this chorus.

        Holloway says, "Tomorrow we start on the western wing—thoughts on design approach?"

        Everyone starts contributing ideas: Runner's acoustic considerations; Velvet's aesthetic planning; Remedy's environmental enhancements; Florence's defensive integration.

        Then they all turn to me.

        They ask, "Kira, what do humans need in western wing spaces?"

        My voice—*as a community member.* Not as a guest.

        I share my thoughts: human need for windows even if we're underground—maybe Velvet's translucent growth; temperature regulation—Remedy's compounds; comfortable sleeping arrangements—Velvet's ergonomic designs.

        Everyone listens, integrates my input, and builds on my suggestions.

        This is what harmony sounds like—not everyone singing the same note, but everyone singing their own note, creating something richer together.

        Scout bounces contentedly against my leg. They knew. They always knew I belonged here.

        The community settles into a comfortable silence—exhausted from rebuilding, satisfied with progress, at peace with each other.

        I look around at these weird, wonderful plant people who somehow created space for a random human to find home.

        ¶

        I don't want to leave.

        This accidental community of bureaucratic aliens has become more home than anywhere I've been in years—maybe ever.

        Buddy chimes in my mind, "Kira! I'm detecting something unusual in the communication array!"

        I say, "What?"

        Buddy says, "Signal. Definitely artificial. Possibly human origin. Should I investigate?"

        Everyone's looking at me—they heard my side of the conversation, wondering what Buddy's saying.

        "Possible signal," I tell them. "Maybe human."

        The atmosphere shifts immediately.

        Human signal.

        Possible rescue.

        Everything just changed. Again.
      </text>
